messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- /admin/register

Notes on path:
- The endpoint is defined in AdminController.newAdmin with @RequestMapping(value = "/admin/register", method = RequestMethod.POST). There is no additional class-level prefix shown in the file, so the full path is /admin/register. No path parameters are present.

HTTP methods acceptability (based on code)
- All methods acceptable: false
  - The code defines only POST for /admin/register (the newAdmin method). There are no mappings for other HTTP methods on this path.

Individual methods
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: true
  - Although not explicitly mapped in code, Spring (Spring Boot) typically handles OPTIONS automatically for endpoints with mappings, returning appropriate Allow headers. This is not implemented by an explicit method in code, but is generally supported by the framework.
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation
- The newAdmin endpoint is mapped only to POST at /admin/register. Therefore, only POST is officially accepted by the code. All other standard methods (GET, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, HEAD, TRACE) do not have mappings for this path, so they are not accepted by the controller.
- OPTIONS is commonly handled by the framework to report allowed methods (and is typically enabled even without an explicit method in code). Thus, OPTIONS is considered acceptable from a framework-support perspective, even though there is no explicit OPTIONS handler in the code.
- The full path given assumes no additional global prefix. If the project defines a global API prefix elsewhere (not shown in the provided file), the actual deployed path could differ. Based strictly on the provided code, /admin/register is the endpoint path.
